> Most likely it is an attempt to make compression work if the input data is chunked to very small pieces.

@jrudolph Maybe I understand it wrong, or something isn't right - [this line](https://github.com/playframework/playframework/pull/6813/files#diff-dc46281aa6759e9b0b71d023b83fc87aR66) uses `splitAt`, when the buffer is smaller than the `chunkSize` (say 3 vs 8192), it will still produce the entire buffer (3) and push. So if the Http.Chunked is a sequence of small chunks, Gzip is still compressing small chunks.

> yeah it would hold back until no data is incoming anymore, but it should still push all the data out, if the source completes.

@schmitch My biggest problem of this is about resizing/concatenating chunks and more-importantly, the timing of the completion of each chunk. A very late second chunk will cause the delay of the first chunk's completion (when the browser completely receives the whole), if the first chunk is a script tag for the browser to eval, then the timing of the execution of that script tag is hugely delayed. Service's own server behaves in such a way really catches users by surprise, as they are not seeing the same thing as what they send/expect.
